# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: demelza-hospice-care-for-children
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station focuses on alternative and indie music.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The Broadcasting Act 1990 allowed for the launch of independent national radio (INR) stations in the United Kingdom.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The Radio Authority was mandated to award three INR licences, one of which (INR1) had to be for a "non-pop" station (which was awarded to Classic FM), and one of which had to be for a predominantly speech-based service (this would be advertised later as INR3 and awarded to Talk Radio).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The remaining licence was to be open to "all-comers".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The licences were to be awarded to the highest cash bidder, providing that the applicant met criteria set down in the Broadcasting Act.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The second national licence, INR2, would take over the 1197 kHz and 1215 kHz medium wave (AM) frequencies, which were to be relinquished by BBC Radio 3.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The TV-am/Virgin consortium was awarded the licence in April 1992, after the Radio Authority said that it was not satisfied that Independent National Broadcasting would be able to sustain the service.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Later that year, TV-am lost its ITV franchise and its stake in the radio station was sold in March 1993 to Apax Partners, JP Morgan Investment Corporation and Sir David Frost.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station launched as Virgin 1215 at 12:15 pm on 30 April 1993.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The original line-up of DJs included Richard Skinner, Russ Williams, Jono Coleman, Mitch Johnson, Graham Dene, Nick Abbot, Wendy Lloyd, Tommy Vance, Emperor Rosko and Dave Fanning.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Chris Evans was also hired to present a Saturday morning show, following his success at BBC GLR in the weekend mid-morning slot.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The show, *The Big Red Mug Show*, was sponsored by Nescafé.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Other key presenters included Nicky Horne, Howard Pearce, Lynn Parsons and Jonathan Ross.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The first song played was INXS' cover version of the Steppenwolf song "Born to be Wild".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Richard Branson was the first voice to be heard, live from the Virgin Megastore in Manchester, with Richard Skinner the first voice back in the London studios.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Skinner was also programme director, a role he shared with John Revell.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] John Pearson was launch sales director, a role he had previously held at LBC.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Andy Mollett was launch finance director.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] David Campbell, previously managing director of one of Virgin's post-production television companies, was the chief executive at launch.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] From before its launch on AM, Virgin Radio was campaigning for a national FM network.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Initially, it lobbied for Radio 4's FM network to be made available and then, when the Radio Authority launched a consultation on the use of the 105–108 MHz band, it lobbied for it to be set aside as a national network.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The Radio Authority decided, however, that 105–108 MHz would be licensed to new local and regional stations and Virgin Radio applied for and won one of the new FM licences advertised in London as a result.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Virgin Radio launched on 105.8 MHz FM in London on 10 April 1995 beginning with a message from broadcaster David Frost at 6 am followed by the *Russ 'n' Jono breakfast show*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Part of the licence requirements for the London service meant that a daily London opt-out was broadcast on FM, presented initially by Rowland Rivron.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Within a year, Virgin Group was considering the next steps for the radio station, including the option of a flotation or buying back the shares of JP Morgan, Apax and Sir David Frost.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In May 1997, it was announced that Capital Radio had agreed to acquire Virgin Radio in an £87 million deal.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Capital's plans included moving Virgin Radio from 1 Golden Square to Capital's Leicester Square building and splitting programming between the AM and FM services.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The Radio Authority approved the acquisition, but Nigel Griffiths, the Consumer Affairs Minister, referred the takeover to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission (MMC).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The MMC report into the takeover would not be issued until January 1998, and would recommend that the deal could only go ahead if Capital Gold was sold or Virgin's London FM licence was excluded from the deal.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] However, the delay in approval of the Capital acquisition would ultimately lead to the deal not going through.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In January 1997, Chris Evans left his role as presenter of the *Radio 1 Breakfast Show* as a result of a disagreement between him and the programme controller Matthew Bannister (Evans had asked for Fridays off to allow more time for him to work on his Channel 4 television show, TFI Friday).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Evans was keen to return to radio and it had been reported that his agent, Michael Foster, had approached Matthew Bannister to ask if Evans would be allowed to be return to Radio 1, and he had gone as far as commencing negotiations to buy Talk Radio.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Richard Branson wanted Evans to work for Virgin Radio, so much so that he joined him on a Concorde flight to New York to try to persuade him to join as the drive time presenter.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In the end, Virgin Radio hired Evans to present the breakfast show, replacing the incumbent *Russ 'n' Jono show* (presented by Russ Williams and Jonathan Coleman).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] His show started on 13 October 1997, the same day that Zoë Ball started as Evans' replacement on Radio 1.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The initial contract would only be for ten weeks, until the MMC announced its decision on the Capital Radio takeover.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Evans approached David Campbell to discuss buying the radio station and, with Michael Foster's help, they put together a deal to buy it with venture capital supplied by Apax Partners and Paribas, with Virgin Group retaining a 20% stake in the business.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The deal was announced on 8 December 1997, and would see the formation of the Ginger Media Group, an umbrella company overseeing Virgin Radio and producing programmes such as TFI Friday.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Evans' ownership of Virgin Radio started well, with a breakfast show audience increase of 660,000 to 2.2m in his first three months.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In August 1998, Evans took a spur of the moment decision one weekend to launch a Saturday afternoon show called *Rock 'n' Roll Football*, which continues to be broadcast on Absolute Radio.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] From 5 October 1998, Virgin Radio started simulcasts of the breakfast show on Sky One each morning for an hour between 7.30 and 8.30 am When a track was played on the radio, viewers would see a video at the same time.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The start of the new football season in August 1999 saw Terry Venables join Russ Williams in a show that would precede *Rock 'n' Roll Football*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] At the end of 1999, at a time when TV programme Who Wants To Be A Millionaire? had yet to give away its top prize, Virgin Radio set a broadcasting first when Clare Barwick won £1 million at the culmination of "Someone's Going to Be a Millionaire".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The management team at the Ginger Media Group were considering expansion opportunities, including a plan to acquire the *Daily Star* newspaper from United News & Media, and hire Piers Morgan to edit it.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Their plans were stalled, however, when the shareholders got cold feet.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The management team therefore set itself on a strategy to sell the business three years ahead of schedule.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] It hired Goldman Sachs to run the sale process, and considered a public flotation, before selling to the Scottish Media Group for £225 million in March 2000.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The Scottish Media Group, which owned Scottish Television and the Herald newspaper, fought off other bidders including Clear Channel, NRJ and Guardian Media Group.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Evans personally made £75 million out of the sale.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Evans was subsequently fired by his new employer in 2001 for failing to report into work for five consecutive days while reportedly partying with his then wife Billie Piper.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Chief executive John Pearson, who had been with the station since before launch, resigned in April 2005, and was replaced by Fru Hazlitt, who had previously been managing director of Yahoo!
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On 13 June 2006, SMG plc signed a deal with YooMedia to make Virgin Radio available on Freeview.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On 12 April 2007, it was announced that SMG plc was to sell Virgin Radio, to enable the company to focus on its television station, STV.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On 30 May 2008 SMG sold Virgin Radio to TIML Golden Square Limited, a subsidiary of The Times Group for £53.2 million, with £15 million set aside for rebranding.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] TIML was given 90 days' grace in which to rebrand the station.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] As part of the deal, Absolute Radio International, operator of two FM licences in Oxford, would manage the station.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On 1 September 2008 it was announced that Virgin Radio would be rebranded as Absolute Radio on 28 September.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] At the same time, changes to the line-up were made known with JK and Joel, Robin Burke, Tony Hadley and John Osborne leaving the station and Allan Lake, Joanna Russell (of Trent FM's Jo & Twiggy) and Tim Shaw joining, though Osborne would return shortly after.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The last song to be played on Virgin Radio was "American Pie" by Don McLean and the first to be played on Absolute Radio was, following the results of an online survey run by the station, "Absolute Beginners" by David Bowie and "A Day in the Life" by The Beatles.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Listening figures for the final quarter of 2008 showed that almost 20% of former Virgin Radio listeners had been lost since the rebranding to Absolute Radio.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The Virgin Radio brand relaunched via DAB and online on 30 March 2016, following a new partnership with Wireless Group and approval of its digital terrestrial commercial radio licence by Ofcom in March 2015.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On 29 July 2013, Bauer Media Group announced it intended to purchase Absolute from The Times Group for an amount believed to be between £20m and £25m, pending regulatory approval.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The deal was cleared by the Office of Fair Trading on 23 December.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Subsequently, by September 2014, all other London-based Bauer stations moved from Mappin House to a refurbished One Golden Square, creating a new national radio hub.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Bauer Radio announced in July 2015 that Absolute Radio would be taking up the 105.2 FM frequency in the West Midlands, previously held by Planet Rock.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute launched on 105.2 FM on 7 September 2015.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station ended transmission on that frequency on 16 December 2018, following Bauer's decision to broadcast Greatest Hits Radio on FM across the West Midlands.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In March 2021, Ofcom approved Bauer's application for permission to alter the FM licence held by the London FM relay of Absolute Radio, enabling the frequency to be used to provide a London variant of Greatest Hits Radio.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Radio continued to be available by way of its national AM and digital transmissions.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Ofcom issued Bauer Radio a £25,000 fine and revoked the medium wave licence on 13 February 2023.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In 2022, Bauer said it would vacate One Golden Square and move to The Lantern, 75 Hampstead Road in Euston.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The last broadcasts from the Golden Square studios took place in April 2024.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] A year after launch, David Campbell was quoted as saying that "the music policy was wrong, even though Virgin had lots of research to suggest it was doing what listeners said they wanted.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] We did something we should never do: pursue critical acclaim, playing obscure tracks, gaining the praise of the music press." The station's approach had been to mix in more familiar music.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Fru Hazlitt, when interviewed for *The Guardian* in September 2006, described the type of music the station championed: "It's pretty much mainstream rock festival-type music.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The music policy continues to focus on guitar-based rock, mostly British.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On 14 July 2022, Absolute Radio launched Absolute Radio Premium where users can listen to the various stations without advert breaks and with the ability to skip a song.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The service also offers five exclusive stations: Absolute Radio Acoustic, Absolute Radio Classic Country, Andy Bush's Indie Disco 24/7, Through the Decades and Haven't Heard It for Ages.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Virgin Radio's original line-up included Russ Williams, Richard Skinner, Mitch Johnson, Tommy Vance, Jonathan Coleman and Nick Abbot.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Other past presenters on the network include Danny Baker, Robin Banks, Kelly-Anne Smith, Vicki Butler-Henderson, Robin Burke.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] From the 2010–11 to the 2015–16 seasons, Absolute Radio broadcast live commentary of 32 Premier League games on Saturday afternoons.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Ian Wright joined the station to host a post-match phone-in programme, as well as a regular music show on Absolute Radio 90s and a football podcast.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] From 2013 to 2014, Absolute Radio held UK radio rights to American football's National Football League.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In 2021, Absolute Radio commissioned its first scripted comedy series, *Rockanory*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Based on a number of *Rock Star Babylon* stories by former *Now Show* comedian Jon Holmes, the series featured the voices of Shaun Keaveny, Jon Culshaw and Jake Yapp.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Short episodes were broadcast Monday to Thursday at 11 pm for six weeks from 6 September 2021.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station broadcast from studios in One Golden Square until April 2024.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] It currently broadcasts from Bauer's building The Lantern, near Euston railway station in London.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The 1215 kHz frequency (247 metres) was used, in selected areas only, by the BBC Light Programme until 1967.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] It was then used nationally as the original home of BBC Radio 1 until 22 November 1978, then from 23 November 1978 until 28 February 1992 by BBC Radio 3.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In 1992–1993, Virgin replaced the valve-based transmitters at the ex-BBC transmitter sites it acquired with solid-state transmitters.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Virgin Radio 1215 AM then broadcast from 30 April 1993 to 28 September 2008, and Absolute Radio 1215 AM broadcast from 29 September 2008 to 19 January 2023.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In a number of areas, particularly where the signals from the main 1215 transmitters overlapped with each other, the station used filler transmitters on different frequencies.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On Wednesday 4 January 2023, Bauer Media Group announced that all the station's remaining AM transmitters would be turned off and that it would no longer be broadcasting on AM from Friday 20 January, turning Absolute Radio into a digital-only station.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On Leona's own show, to avoid duplicating her announcement, she introduced the radio-themed songs, even fulfilling requests.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station closed on AM at midnight on Friday 20 January 2023, with "Absolute Beginners" by David Bowie being the last ever song being broadcast on its AM frequencies.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The last words the announcers said were, "...and to 1215 AM: Thanks.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] You were brilliant." During this split link, the digital version of Absolute Radio ran an Elton John-related segment.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] From midnight on Friday 20 January 2023, a closedown loop (read by Leona Graham as the station voice) carried information advising listeners stating that Absolute Radio "is no longer available on AM" and redirecting listeners to DAB, and the Absolute Radio mobile and smart speaker applications.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On Monday 23 January 2023, the transmitters for its AM service began to be switched off.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In the summer of 1993, Virgin Radio began broadcasting in stereo on the Astra 1A satellite on an audio sub-carrier of the Sky News channel.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] This service ceased on 1 July 2001 in anticipation of Sky's cessation of its analogue satellite service.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Virgin Radio was one of the first 20 radio stations which joined the Sky Digital service on 20 November 1999.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Carried on Astra 2A, it launched on the channel 917 of the Sky EPG, and then could be found on Astra 2G as Absolute Radio on channel 0107 of SKY UK EPG.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Then at the end of 2023 Absolute Radio and its sister channels were removed from Sky after their owner wanted to focus on a more digital market.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Radio also broadcasts through the Eutelsat 9B satellite unencrypted signal at 12.092 MHz, H polarization, azimuth 9°E.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station was available on 105.8 FM from the Crystal Palace transmitting station in London.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In February 2021 Bauer applied to Ofcom for permission to amend the FM broadcast licence to allow the frequency to be used for a London relay of Greatest Hits Radio; Absolute Radio will remain available in London through its retained digital outlets.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station was previously available in the West Midlands on 105.2 FM from the Sutton Coldfield transmitter between 7 September 2015 and 16 December 2018.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Virgin Radio launched its first website on 7 March 1996.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Designed by AKQA, it hosted a live RealAudio stream, making it the first European radio station to stream 24-hours a day on the internet.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station went on to redesign the website a further six times as Virgin Radio.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Streaming audio formats and presentation developed over time: QuickTime streaming was added in July 1999, an interactive media player launched in October 1999, an Ogg-Vorbis stream was launched in June 2003, and HE-AAC and Ogg-FLAC streams were launched in December 2009.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In Autumn 2012 it launched the Opus Streaming Trial as part of the Listen Labs, including streams for all seven stations in 24, 64 and 96 kbit/s.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] This trial was cancelled without further notice in autumn 2014, along with the live webcams and the public playlist API.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In 2001, Virgin Radio joined the Measurecast and Arbitron internet broadcasting measurement services.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Both measurement services have since closed.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In 2009, Absolute Radio started publishing its internet listening and download statistics.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Virgin Radio was also among the first to explore the opportunities for delivering its services to mobile phones.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In 2009, Absolute Radio launched an application for the Apple iPhone and tagging for the Apple iPod Nano.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In 2010 applications were released for the Amazon Kindle, the Nokia Ovi Store, the BlackBerry and Windows Phone 7 and Absolute Radio was selected as a launch partner for the Apple iAd mobile advertising network.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In January 2014, Absolute Radio Network has restricted the access to the internet radio on their own website to UK listeners only, and removed their apps for iPhone and Android in non-UK app stores.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] A number of subsidiary stations to Virgin Radio and Absolute Radio have been launched as online and digital radio services over recent years, many being established during the period when SMG plc was in charge of the station.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The stations were collectively known as the **Virgin Radio Network** (now the **Absolute Radio Network**).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] All Absolute branded channels broadcast online and via smartphone apps, with several also transmitted over DAB and digital television platforms.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] A radio station on DAB, Virgin Media, Sky and the internet playing classic rock from the 1960s to the 1990s.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Launched as Virgin Radio Classic Rock in 2000 as part of SMG Radio's strategy to trade total network listening hours at a time when analogue listening hours had been falling.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The service was rebranded as Absolute Radio Classic Rock in 2008.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Launched on 22 November 2011, Absolute 60s is the sixth radio station launched under the Absolute branding.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station is broadcast on DAB, some digital television networks, and online.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station has defined itself as "the home of the Beatles, Stones and Mo-Town".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] With The Beatles and The Rolling Stones as highlights of the station's broadcasts, it plays music originating from the 1960s.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Pete Mitchell was the main daytime presenter, returning to Golden Square: he was last on Virgin Radio in 2005 hosting the Breakfast show with Geoff Lloyd.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Launched on 29 November 2011, Absolute 70s is the seventh radio station launched under the Absolute branding.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station is broadcast on DAB and online.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] With Rod Stewart, David Bowie and Prince as highlights of the station's broadcast, it plays music originating from the 1970s.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Richard Skinner, another previous DJ from the Virgin Radio days, returned to Golden Square to feature on this station.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] A radio station launched on 4 December 2009 on DAB, Freesat, Sky, Virgin Media and the internet which plays classic hits and is aimed at "reluctant adults" who want to reconnect with the tunes of their youth.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Radio 90s launched on 21 June 2010 on DAB to a 13 million population in London, Essex, Wiltshire, Bristol, Berkshire and Bath.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station is also available on Sky 0201 and online via website and mobile smartphones.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The first song to be played on the station was "Roll with It" by Oasis.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Radio 00s launched on 10 December 2010, online and on DAB in London.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] After an internet poll, the first song played was "Mr.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Radio 10s launched on 18 November 2019 and operates online and on DAB in London.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The first song played by presenter Jay Lawrence was Bastille with "Pompeii".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Radio 20s launched on 24 February 2020 and operates solely online.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The first song played was "Instant History" by Biffy Clyro.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Radio Country previously launched as Country Hits Radio in 2019 before being rebranded on 17 May 2021.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The first song to play after the relaunch was "Jolene" by Dolly Parton.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] In June 2022, an Absolute Radio Classic Country streaming service was added to their Absolute Radio Premium subscription package.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Bauer launched a subscription streaming service for Absolute Radio and KISS, which included five new advert-free radio services under the Absolute Radio brand, alongside the original ten Absolute Radio channels.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Launching at the end of June 2022, the channels included 24/7 versions of *Andy Bush's Indie Disco* programme and *Haven't Heard It For Ages* programme feature, and channels called Through The Decades, Absolute Radio Classic Country and Absolute Radio Acoustic.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] This is a pop up service based around a competition, which gives the listener the chance to pitch a new service to Absolute with the winning entry appearing each February.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The winning idea of the 2024 competition came from Scottish sisters Rachael and Emma Hare, and is called Absolute Radio Sisters.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The service, whose strapline is ‘Where Sibling Rivalry Matters’, plays a mixture of music from the 1990s and 2000s, and will be on air from 12 to 22 February 2024.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Established in 2010, Absolute Radio Extra enabled Absolute to carry its Premier League football coverage on DAB.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] During match coverage, the analogue frequencies of Absolute were split, with the London 105.8 FM service carrying scores-and-music show *Rock 'n Roll Football*, and the national 1215 AM service carrying match commentary.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On DAB, the main Absolute service carried *Rock 'n Roll Football*, with Extra carrying match commentary.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Extra was also used for coverage of music festivals and events (such as V Festival) in addition to the coverage available on the main station.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Radio Extra has subsequently ceased operation: the core Absolute service on DAB continues to relay the shared programming output of the national AM/London FM service.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Radio 40s was a pop-up station in May 2020, which celebrated the 75th anniversary of VE Day.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Radio 40s was also found online and on DAB.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] A radio station on DAB, Virgin Media, Sky and the Internet, playing new music.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Absolute Xtreme was launched (as Virgin Radio Xtreme) on 5 September 2005, by Lali Parikh (Station Manager) with Steve Harris being the main on-air talent.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] On 4 December 2009, Absolute Xtreme was replaced on DAB and digital TV by Absolute Radio 80s.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] dabbl was a user-controlled music radio station broadcast on the Internet and selected local DAB multiplexes 24 hours a day, and on DAB in London from 7 pm to 6 am daily.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Its content was chosen by members of Absolute's VIP Service, who selected songs which were then voted for, and songs with the most votes were played. dabbl has now ceased, its DAB slots outside London taken by Absolute Radio 90s.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Liquid was a station playing indie, alternative and Britpop.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] It ran on DAB in London between 2000 and 2004, with its slot taken by Virgin Radio Classic Rock (now Absolute Classic Rock).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] A radio station on DAB, Virgin Media, Sky and the Internet which played motown, soul and disco music.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Originally named *The Groove*, it was rebranded as a Virgin Radio station in 2004 and closed at the end of 2007.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Launched on 15 June 2006, Virgin Radio Party Classics played party pop music.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The radio station was based on Suggs' *Virgin Party Classics* show broadcast on Virgin Radio.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] The station, which broadcast on Sky Digital and online, closed on 3 October 2006.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/absolute-radio] Virgin Radio Viva, which was due to launch on the new 4 Digital Group platform (which ultimately never launched), was due to be a popular music station aimed at 15- to 29-year-old females.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The **archbishop of Canterbury** is the senior bishop and primate of the Church of England.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In this capacity, they are the diocesan bishop of the diocese of Canterbury, the metropolitan of the province of Canterbury, and the ceremonial head of the worldwide Anglican Communion.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Ecclesial functions aside, the archbishop is also one of the 26 Anglican bishops who sit in the House of Lords as a Lord Spiritual.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The 106th archbishop is Dame Sarah Mullally, who was confirmed on 28 January 2026 and is the first woman to hold the office.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The first archbishop of Canterbury was Augustine, the "Apostle to the English", who was sent to England by Pope Gregory the Great and arrived in 597.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] From Augustine until William Warham the archbishops of Canterbury were in full communion with the Catholic Church.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] During the English Reformation, King Henry VIII broke communion with Rome and proclaimed himself the head of the Church of England.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Thomas Cranmer, appointed in 1533, initially with Rome's approval, thereafter became the first Protestant archbishop of Canterbury and would become one of the most important figures in the development of Anglicanism.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The archbishop is appointed by the British monarch on the advice of the prime minister of the United Kingdom and formally elected by the college of canons of Canterbury Cathedral.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In practice, however, candidates are chosen by the Crown Nominations Commission, a Church of England body which advises the prime minister.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In the last two of these functions, they have an important ecumenical and interfaith role, speaking on behalf of Anglicans in England and worldwide.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The archbishop's main residence is Lambeth Palace in the London Borough of Lambeth.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] They also have lodgings in the Old Palace, Canterbury, located beside Canterbury Cathedral, where the Chair of St Augustine sits.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] As holder of one of the "five great sees" (the others being York, London, Durham and Winchester), the archbishop of Canterbury is *ex officio* one of the Lords Spiritual of the House of Lords.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] They are one of the highest-ranking people in England and the highest ranking non-royal in the United Kingdom's order of precedence.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Since Henry VIII broke with Rome, the archbishops of Canterbury have been selected by the English (British since the Act of Union in 1707) monarch.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Since the 20th century, the appointment of archbishops of Canterbury conventionally alternates between Anglo-Catholics and Evangelicals.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The previous archbishop, Justin Welby, was the 105th holder of the office; he was enthroned at Canterbury Cathedral on 21 March 2013.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] As archbishop he signed himself as *+ Justin Cantuar*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] On 12 November 2024, he announced his decision to resign; he did so effective 7 January 2025.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Two other former archbishops were living as of 2026: George Carey (born 1935), the 103rd archbishop; and Rowan Williams (born 1950), the 104th archbishop.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In addition to their office, the archbishop holds a number of other positions; for example, they are joint president of the Council of Christians and Jews in the United Kingdom.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Some positions they formally hold *ex officio* and others virtually so (the incumbent of the day, although appointed personally, is appointed because of their office).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The archbishop is also a president of Churches Together in England (an ecumenical organisation).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Geoffrey Fisher, 99th archbishop of Canterbury, was the first since 1397 to visit Rome, where he held private talks with Pope John XXIII in 1960.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In 2005, Rowan Williams became the first archbishop of Canterbury to attend a papal funeral since the Reformation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] He also attended the inauguration of Pope Benedict XVI.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The 101st archbishop, Donald Coggan, was the first to attend a papal inauguration, that of Pope John Paul II in 1978.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Since 2002, the archbishop has co-sponsored the Alexandria Middle East Peace process with the Grand Mufti of Egypt.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In July 2008, the archbishop attended a conference of Christians, Jews and Muslims convened by the king of Saudi Arabia at which the notion of the "clash of civilizations" was rejected.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] It has been suggested that the Roman province of Britannia had four archbishops, seated at Londinium (London), Eboracum (York), Lindum Colonia (Lincoln) and Corinium Dobunnorum (Cirencester).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] However, in the 5th and 6th centuries Britannia began to be overrun by pagan, Germanic peoples who came to be known collectively as the Anglo-Saxons.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Of the kingdoms they created, Kent arguably had the closest links with European politics, trade and culture, because it was conveniently situated for communication with continental Europe.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In the late 6th century, King Æthelberht of Kent married a Christian Frankish princess named Bertha, possibly before becoming king, and certainly a number of years before the arrival of the first Christian mission to England.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] He permitted the preaching of Christianity.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The first archbishop of Canterbury was Saint Augustine of Canterbury (not to be confused with Saint Augustine of Hippo), who arrived in Kent in 597 AD, having been sent by Pope Gregory I on a mission to the English.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] He was accepted by King Æthelbert, on his conversion to Christianity, about the year 598.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] It seems that Pope Gregory, ignorant of recent developments in the former Roman province, including the spread of the Pelagian heresy, had intended the new archiepiscopal sees for England to be established in London and York.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In the event, Canterbury was chosen instead of London, owing to political circumstances.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Since then the archbishops of Canterbury have been referred to as occupying the Chair of St.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] A gospel book believed to be directly associated with St Augustine's mission survives in the Parker Library, Corpus Christi College, University of Cambridge, England.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Catalogued as Cambridge *Manuscript 286*, it has been positively dated to 6th-century Italy and this bound book, the St Augustine Gospels, is still used during the swearing-in ceremony of new archbishops of Canterbury.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Before the break with papal authority in the 16th century, the Church of England was an integral part of the Western European church.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The *Report of the Commissioners appointed by his Majesty to inquire into the Ecclesiastical Revenues of England and Wales* (1835) noted the net annual revenue for the Canterbury see was £19,182.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The archbishop of Canterbury exercises metropolitical (or supervisory) jurisdiction over the Province of Canterbury, which encompasses thirty of the forty-two dioceses of the Church of England, with the rest falling within the Province of York.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The four Welsh dioceses were also under the province of Canterbury until 1920 when they were transferred from the established church of England to the disestablished Church in Wales.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The archbishop of Canterbury has a ceremonial provincial *curia*, or court, consisting of some of the senior bishops of their province.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Along with primacy over the archbishop of York, the archbishop of Canterbury also has a precedence of honour over the other bishops of the Anglican Communion.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] They are recognised as *primus inter pares*, or first amongst equals.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] They do not, however, exercise any direct authority in the provinces outside England, except in certain minor roles dictated by Canon in those provinces (for example, they are the judge in the event of an ecclesiastical prosecution against the archbishop of Wales).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] They do hold metropolitical authority over several extra-provincial Anglican churches, and they serve as *ex officio* bishop of the Falkland Islands.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The archbishops of Canterbury and York are both styled as "The Most Reverend"; retired archbishops are styled as "The Right Reverend".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The archbishop is, by convention, appointed to the Privy Council and may, therefore, also use the style of "The Right Honourable" for life, unless later removed from the council.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In formal documents, the archbishop of Canterbury is referred to as "The Most Reverend Forenames, by Divine Providence Lord Archbishop of Canterbury, Primate of All England and Metropolitan".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In debates in the House of Lords, the archbishop is referred to as "The Most Reverend Primate, the Archbishop of Canterbury".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] "The Right Honourable" is not used in either instance.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] They may also be formally addressed as "Your Grace" or, more informally, as "Archbishop".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The surname of the archbishop of Canterbury is not always used in formal documents; often only the first name and see are mentioned.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The archbishop is legally entitled to sign their name as "Cantuar" (the Latin for Canterbury).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The right to use a title as a legal signature is only permitted to bishops, peers of the Realm and peers by courtesy.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Justin Welby as archbishop of Canterbury usually signed as "*+Justin Cantuar:*".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In the English and Welsh order of precedence, the archbishop of Canterbury is ranked above all individuals in the realm, with the exception of the sovereign and members of the royal family.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Immediately below them is the lord chancellor and then the archbishop of York.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The archbishop of Canterbury awards academic degrees, commonly called "Lambeth degrees".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] The archbishop of Canterbury's official residence and office in London is Lambeth Palace.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] They also have an apartment within the Old Palace, next to Canterbury Cathedral which incorporates some 13th-century fabric of the medieval Archbishop's Palace.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] From 1660 to 1902, all the archbishops of Canterbury died in office.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] In 1928, two years before his death, Randall Davidson became the first to voluntarily resign his office.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] All his successors except William Temple (who died in office in 1944) have also resigned their office before death.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Until 2025, all archbishops who retired were immediately given peerages: initially hereditary baronies (although both recipients of such titles died without male heirs and so their titles became extinct on their deaths), and life peerages after the enactment of the Life Peerages Act 1958.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Such titles have allowed retired archbishops to retain the seats in the House of Lords which they held *ex officio* before their retirement.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/archbishop-of-canterbury] Justin Welby, who resigned in January 2025, has not yet received a peerage.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] A **brain tumor** (sometimes referred to as **brain cancer**) occurs when a group of cells within the brain grow out of control, creating a mass.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] There are two main types of tumors: malignant (cancerous) tumors and benign (non-cancerous) tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] These can be further classified as primary tumors, which start within the brain, and secondary tumors, which most commonly have spread from tumors located outside the brain, known as brain metastasis tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] All types of brain tumors may produce symptoms that vary depending on the size of the tumor and the part of the brain that is involved.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Where symptoms exist, they may include headaches, seizures, problems with vision, vomiting and mental changes.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Other symptoms may include difficulty walking, speaking, with sensations, or unconsciousness.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The cause of most brain tumors is unknown, though up to 4% of brain cancers may be caused by CT scan radiation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Uncommon risk factors include exposure to vinyl chloride, Epstein–Barr virus, ionizing radiation, and inherited syndromes such as neurofibromatosis, tuberous sclerosis, and von Hippel-Lindau Disease.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Studies on mobile phone exposure have not shown a clear risk.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The most common types of primary tumors in adults are meningiomas (usually benign) and astrocytomas such as glioblastomas.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In children, the most common type is a malignant medulloblastoma.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Diagnosis is usually by medical examination along with computed tomography (CT) or magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The result is then often confirmed by a biopsy.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Based on the findings, the tumors are divided into different grades of severity.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Treatment may include some combination of surgery, radiation therapy and chemotherapy.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] If seizures occur, anticonvulsant medication may be needed.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Dexamethasone and furosemide are medications that may be used to decrease swelling around the tumor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Some tumors grow gradually, requiring only monitoring and possibly needing no further intervention.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Treatments that use a person's immune system are being studied.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Outcomes for malignant tumors vary considerably depending on the type of tumor and how far it has spread at diagnosis.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Although benign tumors only grow in one area, they may still be life-threatening depending on their size and location.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Malignant glioblastomas usually have very poor outcomes, while benign meningiomas usually have good outcomes.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The average five-year survival rate for all (malignant) brain cancers in the United States is 33%.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Secondary, or metastatic, brain tumors are about four times as common as primary brain tumors, with about half of metastases coming from lung cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Primary brain tumors occur in around 250,000 people a year globally, and make up less than 2% of cancers.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In children younger than 15, brain tumors are second only to acute lymphoblastic leukemia as the most common form of cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In New South Wales, Australia in 2005, the average lifetime economic cost of a case of brain cancer was AU$1.9 million, the greatest of any type of cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The signs and symptoms of brain tumors are broad.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] People may experience symptoms regardless of whether the tumor is benign (not cancerous) or cancerous.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Primary and secondary brain tumors present with similar symptoms, depending on the location, size, and rate of growth of the tumor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] For example, larger tumors in the frontal lobe can cause changes in the ability to think.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] However, a smaller tumor in an area such as Wernicke's area (small area responsible for language comprehension) can result in a greater loss of function.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Headaches as a result of raised intracranial pressure can be an early symptom of brain cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] However, isolated headache without other symptoms is rare, and other symptoms including visual abnormalities may occur before headaches become common.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Certain warning signs for headache exist which make the headache more likely to be associated with brain cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Other associated signs are headaches that are worse in the morning or that subside after vomiting.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The brain is divided into lobes and each lobe or area has its own function.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] A tumour in any of these lobes may affect the area's performance.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The symptoms experienced are often linked to the location of the tumour, but each person may experience something different.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] A person's personality may be altered due to the tumor damaging lobes of the brain.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] More research is needed into the effectiveness and safety of medication for depression in people with brain tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Personality changes can have damaging effects such as unemployment, unstable relationships, and a lack of control.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] A known cause of brain cancers is ionizing radiation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Approximately 4% of brain cancers in the general population are caused by CT-scan radiation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] For brain cancers that follow a CT scan at lags of 2 years or more, it has been estimated that 40% are attributable to CT-scan radiation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The risk of brain cancer is dose dependent, with the relative risk increasing by 0.8 for each 100 gray of ionizing radiation received.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] At this dose, approximately 6391 people would have to be exposed to cause 1 case of brain cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Mutations and deletions of tumor suppressor genes, such as P53, are thought to be the cause of some forms of brain tumor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Inherited conditions, such as Von Hippel–Lindau disease, tuberous sclerosis, multiple endocrine neoplasia, and neurofibromatosis type 2 carry a high risk for the development of brain tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] People with celiac disease have a slightly increased risk of developing brain tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Smoking may increase the risk, but evidence of this remains unclear.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Although studies have not shown any link between cell-phone or mobile-phone radiation and the occurrence of brain tumors, the World Health Organization has classified mobile-phone radiation on the IARC scale into Group 2B – possibly carcinogenic.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The claim that cell-phone usage may cause brain cancer is likely based on epidemiological studies which observed a slight increase in glioma risk among heavy users of wireless phones.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] When those studies were conducted, GSM (2G) phones were in use.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Modern, third-generation (3G) phones emit, on average, about 1% of the energy emitted by those GSM (2G) phones, and therefore the finding of an association between cell-phone usage and increased risk of brain cancer is not based upon current phone usage.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Human brains are surrounded by a system of connective tissue membranes called meninges that separate the brain from the skull.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] This three-layered covering is composed of (from the outside in) the dura mater, arachnoid mater, and pia mater.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The arachnoid and pia are physically connected and thus often considered as a single layer, the *leptomeninges*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Between the arachnoid mater and the pia mater is the subarachnoid space which contains cerebrospinal fluid (CSF).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] This fluid circulates in the narrow spaces between cells and through the cavities in the brain called ventricles, to support and protect the brain tissue.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Blood vessels enter the central nervous system through the perivascular space above the pia mater.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The cells in the blood vessel walls are joined tightly, forming the blood–brain barrier which protects the brain from toxins that might enter through the blood.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Tumors of the meninges are meningiomas and are often benign.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Though not technically a tumor of brain tissue, they are often considered brain tumors since they protrude into the space where the brain is, causing symptoms.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Since they are usually slow-growing tumors, meningiomas can be quite large by the time symptoms appear.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The three largest divisions of the brain are the cerebral cortex, cerebellum and the brainstem.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] These areas are composed of two broad classes of cells: neurons and glia.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] These two cell types are equally numerous in the brain as a whole, although glial cells outnumber neurons roughly 4 to 1 in the cerebral cortex.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Glia come in several types, which perform a number of critical functions, including structural support, metabolic support, insulation, and guidance of development.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Primary tumors of the glial cells are called gliomas and often are malignant by the time they are diagnosed.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The thalamus and hypothalamus are major divisions of the diencephalon, with the pituitary gland and pineal gland attached at the bottom; tumors of the pituitary and pineal gland are often benign.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The brainstem lies between the large cerebral cortex and the spinal cord.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] It is divided into the midbrain, pons, and medulla oblongata.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] There are no specific signs or symptoms for brain cancer, but the presence of a combination of symptoms and the lack of alternative causes may indicate a brain tumor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] A medical history aids in the diagnosis.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Clinical and laboratory investigations will serve to exclude infections as the cause of the symptoms.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Brain tumors, when compared to tumors in other areas of the body, pose a challenge for diagnosis.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Commonly, radioactive tracers are uptaken in large volumes in tumors due to the high activity of tumor cells, allowing for radioactive imaging of the tumor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] However, most of the brain is separated from the blood by the blood–brain barrier (BBB), a membrane that exerts a strict control over what substances are allowed to pass into the brain.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Therefore, many tracers that may reach tumors in other areas of the body easily would be unable to reach brain tumors until there was a disruption of the BBB by the tumor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Disruption of the BBB is well imaged via MRI or CT scan, and is therefore regarded as the main diagnostic indicator for malignant gliomas, meningiomas, and brain metastases.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Medical imaging plays a central role in the diagnosis of brain tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Early imaging methods – invasive and sometimes dangerous – such as pneumoencephalography and cerebral angiography have been replaced by non-invasive, high-resolution techniques, especially magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and computed tomography (CT) scans.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] MRI with contrast enhancement is the preferred imaging test in the diagnosis of brain tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Glioblastomas usually enhance with contrast on T1 MRI weighted MRI imaging, and on T2 with FLAIR imaging showing hyperintense cerebral edema.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Low grade gliomas are usually hypointense on T1 MRI, and hyperintense with T2 with FLAIR MRI.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Meningiomas are usually homogenously enhanced with dural thickening on MRI.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Treatment with radiation can lead to treatment induced changes in the brain, including radiation necrosis (death of brain tissue due to radiation treatments) visible on brain imaging and which can be difficult to differentiate from tumor recurrence.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Maximal safe surgical resection (to preserve as much neurological function as possible) and histologic examination of the tumor is also required to aid in the diagnosis.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Cancer cells may have specific characteristics.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Atypia: an indication of abnormality of a cell (which may be indicative of malignancy).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Significance of the abnormality is highly dependent on context.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Neoplasia: the (uncontrolled) division of cells that is characteristic of cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Necrosis: the (premature) death of cells, caused by external factors such as infection, toxin or trauma.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Local hypoxia, or the deprivation of adequate oxygen supply to certain areas of the brain, including within the tumor, as the tumor grows and recruits local blood vessels.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Tumors can be benign or malignant, can occur in different parts of the brain, and may be classified as primary or secondary.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] A primary tumor is one that has started in the brain, as opposed to a metastatic tumor, which is one that has spread to the brain from another area of the body.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The incidence of metastatic tumors is approximately four times greater than primary tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Tumors may or may not be symptomatic: some tumors are discovered because the patient has symptoms, others show up incidentally on an imaging scan, or at an autopsy.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Grading of the tumors of the central nervous system commonly occurs on a 4-point scale (I-IV) created by the World Health Organization in 1993.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Grade I tumors are the least severe and commonly associated with long-term survival, with severity and prognosis worsening as the grade increases.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Low-grade tumors are often benign, while higher grades are aggressively malignant and/or metastatic.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Other grading scales do exist, many based upon the same criteria as the WHO scale and graded from I-IV.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Secondary tumors of the brain are metastatic and have spread to the brain from cancers originating in another organ.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Metastatic spread is usually by the blood.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The most common types of cancers that spread to the brain are lung cancer (accounting for over half of all cases), breast cancer, melanoma skin cancer, kidney cancer and colon cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Brain tumors can be cancerous (malignant) or non-cancerous (benign).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] However, the definitions of malignant or benign neoplasms differ from those commonly used in other types of cancerous or non-cancerous neoplasms in the body.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In cancers elsewhere in the body, three malignant properties differentiate benign tumors from malignant forms of cancer: benign tumors are self-limited and do not invade or metastasize.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In 2016, the WHO restructured their classifications of some categories of gliomas to include distinct genetic mutations that have been useful in differentiating tumor types, prognoses, and treatment responses.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Genetic mutations are typically detected via immunohistochemistry, a technique that visualizes the presence or absence of a targeted protein via staining.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] A medical team generally assesses the treatment options and presents them to the person affected and their family.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Survival rates in primary brain tumors depend on the type of tumor, age, functional status of the patient, the extent of surgical removal and other factors specific to each case.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Standard care for anaplastic oligodendrogliomas and anaplastic oligoastrocytomas is surgery followed by radiotherapy.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] One study found a survival benefit for the addition of chemotherapy to radiotherapy after surgery, compared with radiotherapy alone.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Surgical resection of the greatest extent of contrast enhancing tumor possible (gross total resection) is associated with increased overall and progression free survival in those with glioblastoma.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Gross total resection is often required in other brain tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Minimally invasive techniques are becoming the dominant trend in neurosurgical oncology.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The main objective of surgery is to remove as many tumor cells as possible, with complete removal being the best outcome and cytoreduction ("debulking") of the tumor may otherwise be done.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Due to the infiltrative nature of glioblastomas, total resection is usually unachievable and progression after surgery usually occurs, with progression occurring about 7 months after surgery.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Many meningiomas, with the exception of some tumors located at the skull base, can be successfully removed surgically.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Most pituitary adenomas can be removed surgically, often using a minimally invasive approach through the nasal cavity and skull base (trans-nasal, trans-sphenoidal approach).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Large pituitary adenomas require a craniotomy (opening of the skull) for their removal.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Radiotherapy, including stereotactic approaches, is reserved for inoperable cases.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Postoperative radiotherapy and chemotherapy are integral parts of the therapeutic standard for malignant tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Multiple metastatic tumors are generally treated with radiotherapy and chemotherapy rather than surgery and the prognosis in such cases is determined by the primary tumor, and is generally poor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The goal of radiation therapy is to kill tumor cells while leaving normal brain tissue unharmed.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In standard external beam radiation therapy, multiple treatments of standard-dose "fractions" of radiation are applied to the brain.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] This process is repeated for a total of 10 to 30 treatments, depending on the type of tumor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] This additional treatment provides some patients with improved outcomes and better survival rates.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Radiosurgery is a treatment method that uses computerized calculations to focus radiation at the site of the tumor while minimizing the radiation dose to the surrounding brain.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Radiosurgery may be an adjunct to other treatments, or it may represent the primary treatment technique for some tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Forms used include stereotactic radiosurgery, such as Gamma knife, Cyberknife or Novalis Tx radiosurgery.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Radiotherapy is the most common treatment for secondary brain tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The amount of radiotherapy depends on the size of the area of the brain affected by cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Conventional external beam "whole-brain radiotherapy treatment" (WBRT) or "whole-brain irradiation" may be suggested if there is a risk that other secondary tumors will develop in the future.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Stereotactic radiotherapy is usually recommended in cases involving fewer than three small secondary brain tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Radiotherapy may be used following, or in some cases in place of, resection of the tumor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Forms of radiotherapy used for brain cancer include external beam radiation therapy, the most common, and brachytherapy and proton therapy, the last especially used for children.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] People who receive stereotactic radiosurgery (SRS) and whole-brain radiation therapy (WBRT) for the treatment of metastatic brain tumors have more than twice the risk of developing learning and memory problems than those treated with SRS alone.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Results of a 2021 systematic review found that when using SRS as the initial treatment, survival or death related to brain metastasis was not greater than alone versus SRS with WBRT.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Postoperative conventional daily radiotherapy improves survival for adults with good functional well-being and high grade glioma compared to no postoperative radiotherapy.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Hypofractionated radiation therapy has similar efficacy for survival as compared to conventional radiotherapy, particularly for individuals aged 60 and older with glioblastoma.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Patients undergoing chemotherapy are administered drugs designed to kill tumor cells.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Although chemotherapy may improve overall survival in patients with the most malignant primary brain tumors, it does so in only about 20 percent of patients.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Chemotherapy is often used in young children instead of radiation, as radiation may have negative effects on the developing brain.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The decision to prescribe this treatment is based on a patient's overall health, type of tumor, and extent of cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The toxicity and many side effects of the drugs, and the uncertain outcome of chemotherapy in brain tumors puts this treatment further down the line of treatment options with surgery and radiation therapy preferred.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] UCLA Neuro-Oncology publishes real-time survival data for patients with a diagnosis of glioblastoma.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] They are the only institution in the United States that displays how brain tumor patients are performing on current therapies.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] They also show a listing of chemotherapy agents used to treat high-grade glioma tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Genetic mutations have significant effects on the effectiveness of chemotherapy.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Gliomas with IDH1 or IDH2 mutations respond better to chemotherapy than those without the mutation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Loss of chromosome arms 1p and 19q also indicate better response to chemoradiation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] A shunt may be used to relieve symptoms caused by intracranial pressure, by reducing the build-up of fluid (hydrocephalus) caused by the blockage of the free flow of cerebrospinal fluid.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] For those with brain tumors, anti-seizure prophylactic (preventative) medications are not usually recommended.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] However, anti-epileptics are used in those with seizures.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Cerebral edema secondary to brain tumors is managed by corticosteroids.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Dexamethasone is the preferred corticosteroid due to its long half-life and reduced effect on water retention (mineralcorticoid activity).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Bevacizumab (an anti-VEGFA antibody) may improve cerebral edema in those that are unresponsive to steroids.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The prognosis of brain cancer depends on the type of cancer diagnosed.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Medulloblastoma has a good prognosis with chemotherapy, radiotherapy, and surgical resection while glioblastoma has a median survival of only 15 months even with aggressive chemoradiotherapy and surgery.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Brainstem gliomas have the poorest prognosis of any form of brain cancer, with most patients dying within one year, even with therapy that typically consists of radiation to the tumor along with corticosteroids.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] However, one type, focal brainstem gliomas in children, seems open to exceptional prognosis and long-term survival has frequently been reported.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Prognosis is also affected by presentation of genetic mutations.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Certain mutations provide better prognosis than others.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] IDH1 and IDH2 mutations in gliomas, as well as deletion of chromosome arms 1p and 19q, generally indicate better prognosis.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] TP53, ATRX, EGFR, PTEN, and TERT mutations are also useful in determining prognosis.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Glioblastoma is the most aggressive (grade 4) and most common form of a malignant primary brain tumor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Even when aggressive multimodality therapy consisting of radiotherapy, chemotherapy, and surgical excision is used, median survival is only 15–18 months.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Standard therapy for glioblastoma consists of maximal surgical resection of the tumor, followed by radiotherapy between two and four weeks after the surgical procedure to remove the cancer, then by chemotherapy, such as temozolomide.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Most patients with glioblastoma take a corticosteroid, typically dexamethasone, during their illness to relieve symptoms.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Experimental treatments include targeted therapy, gamma knife radiosurgery, boron neutron capture therapy, gene therapy, and chemowafer implants.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Oligodendrogliomas are incurable but slowly progressive malignant brain tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] They can be treated with surgical resection, chemotherapy, radiotherapy or a combination.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] For some suspected low-grade (grade II) tumors, only a course of watchful waiting and symptomatic therapy is opted for.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] These tumors show co-deletions of the p and q arms of chromosome 1 and chromosome 19 respectively (1p19q co-deletion) and have been found to be especially chemosensitive with one report claiming them to be one of the most chemosensitive tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] A median survival of up to 16.7 years has been reported for grade II oligodendrogliomas.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Acoustic neuromas are non-cancerous tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] They can be treated with surgery, radiation therapy, or observation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Early intervention with surgery or radiation is recommended to prevent progressive hearing loss.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The incidence of brain tumors is higher in developed countries.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] This could be explained by undiagnosed tumor-related deaths in resource limited or lower income countries or by early deaths caused by other poverty-related causes that preempt a patient's life before tumors develop.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The incidence of CNS tumors in the United States, Israel, and the Nordic countries is relatively high, while Japan and Asian countries have a lower incidence.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In the United States in 2015, approximately 166,039 people were living with brain or other central nervous system tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Over 2018, it was projected that there would be 23,880 new cases of brain tumors and 16,830 deaths in 2018 as a result, accounting for 1.4 percent of all cancers and 2.8 percent of all cancer deaths.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Median age of diagnosis was 58 years old, while median age of death was 65.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Diagnosis was slightly more common in males, at approximately 7.5 cases per 100 000 people, while females saw 2 fewer at 5.4.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Deaths as a result of brain cancer were 5.3 per 100 000 for males, and 3.6 per 100 000 for females, making brain cancer the 10th leading cause of cancer death in the United States.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Overall lifetime risk of developing brain cancer is approximated at 0.6 percent for men and women.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Brain, other CNS or intracranial tumors are the ninth most common cancer in the UK (around 10,600 people were diagnosed in 2013), and it is the eighth most common cause of cancer death (around 5,200 people died in 2012).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] White British patients with brain tumour are 30% more likely to die within a year of diagnosis than patients from other ethnicities.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In the United States more than 28,000 people under 20 are estimated to have a brain tumor.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] About 3,720 new cases of brain tumors are expected to be diagnosed in those under 15 in 2019.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] There is some debate as to the reasons; one theory is that the trend is the result of improved diagnosis and reporting, since the jump occurred at the same time that MRIs became available widely, and there was no coincident jump in mortality.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Central nervous system tumors make up 20–25 percent of cancers in children.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The average survival rate for all primary brain cancers in children is 74%.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Brain cancer is the most common cancer in children under 19 and results in more deaths in this age group than leukemia.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] The most common brain tumor types in children (0–14) are: pilocytic astrocytoma, malignant glioma, medulloblastoma, neuronal and mixed neuronal-glial tumors, and ependymoma.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In children under 2, about 70% of brain tumors are medulloblastomas, ependymomas, and low-grade gliomas.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Less commonly, and seen usually in infants, are teratomas and atypical teratoid rhabdoid tumors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Germ cell tumors, including teratomas, make up just 3% of pediatric primary brain tumors, but the worldwide incidence varies significantly.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In the UK, 429 children aged 14 and under are diagnosed with a brain tumour on average each year, and 563 children and young people under the age of 19 are diagnosed.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Cancer immunotherapy is being actively studied.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] For malignant gliomas no therapy has been shown to improve life expectancy as of 2015.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] In 2000, researchers used the vesicular stomatitis virus (VSV) to infect and kill cancer cells without affecting healthy cells.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Subsequently, in preparation for human clinical trials, this technology was further developed by Tocagen (a pharmaceutical company primarily focused on brain cancer treatments) as a combination treatment (Toca 511 & Toca FC).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] This has been under investigation since 2010 in a Phase I/II clinical trial for the potential treatment of recurrent high-grade glioma including glioblastoma and anaplastic astrocytoma.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/brain-tumor] Efforts to detect and monitor development and treatment response of brain tumors by liquid biopsy from blood, cerebrospinal fluid or urine, are in the early stages of development.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker, who as a member of Co-Co had earlier represented the UK at the 1978 Eurovision Song Contest, left Bucks Fizz in 1993 to concentrate on her television career.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In the mid-1980s, while still with the group, Baker started a career as a television presenter, including for the children's show *How Dare You!* (1984) and *The Saturday Picture Show* (1985–1986).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In 1987, she joined *Record Breakers* and remained as a co-host until 1997.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Her own show *Eggs 'n' Baker*, featuring cooking and guest musical performers, ran for five years from 1988.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Her other appearances include *Popstar to Operastar* (2011), *Celebrity Mastermind* (2013 and 2022) and in the tenth series of *Dancing on Ice* (2017).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In 2004, Baker, Shelley Preston and fellow original Bucks Fizz member Mike Nolan started performing together as the Original Bucks Fizz.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Another original Bucks Fizz member, Jay Aston, replaced Preston 2009.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] The group went through rebrandings, and in 2017, they renamed themselves as the Fizz and worked on new material.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker has also appeared in several pantomimes, and in a musical theatre production of *Footloose*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Cheryl Baker was born as Rita Maria Crudgington on 8 March 1954 in Bethnal Green, London.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Her father Ted worked as a cobbler, and her mother was called Doll.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] After leaving school she worked in a stockbroker's office, and attended an evening amateur operatic group.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] She joined a band called Bressingham Spire when she was 17, but they soon disbanded and she joined another group, which included Mike Read.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] After this she became part of Mother's Pride, later renamed as Co-Co, after seeing an advert for new members for the group in *Melody Maker*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] The group entered *A Song for Europe* in 1976 with the song "Wake Up".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] They came second, being beaten by (eventual Eurovision winners) Brotherhood of Man by two points.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] The group continued to perform together and in 1978, they entered *A Song for Europe* again with "The Bad Old Days".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] This time they won and went on to perform for the UK in Paris.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] The song managed 11th place – the lowest placing by a UK entry up to that point.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] John Kennedy O'Connor, author of *The Eurovision Song Contest – The Official History*, described the group giving "a very weak and off-key vocal performance".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker later reflected that she had been "totally disillusioned, that I'd let the country down.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] I can't honestly say I enjoyed anything about my first Eurovision experience even though it had been a childhood ambition." The song became a hit single, reaching 13 in the UK Singles Chart.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] The shortlisting was done on the basis of a recording submitted on cassette tapes, which was performed by Martin, songwriter Andy Hill, and Mike Nolan, but Martin decided to put together a group with two men and two women, not including herself or Hill.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] The group, called Bucks Fizz and consisting of Nolan, Baker, Bobby Gee and Jay Aston, won *A Song For Europe*, which meant they became the UK representative at the Eurovision Song Contest on 4 April 1981.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] The song went on to win by a margin of four points ahead of the second-placed German entry.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] O'Connor wrote that "the group sang way off-key, but had such enthusiasm that the judges overlooked this in favour of the song".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] As part of the choreography, the male members of the group tore skirts off the women at the last chorus, revealing shorter skirts below.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker was one of the few artists to take part in Eurovision to win at their second attempt.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] "Making Your Mind Up" became a number one hit in the UK, Austria, Belgium, Denmark, Germany, Ireland, Israel, the Netherlands, Norway, Spain, and Norway.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] She has said that she does not like the song, as it is "not her kind of music at all".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker and the rest of the group had two more British number ones; "The Land of Make Believe" (1981) and "My Camera Never Lies" (1982).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] They had further successful singles, but after *When We Were Young* (1983), their next records sold less well.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker and Aston appeared in cameo roles in the video for "Who's That Girl?" (1983) by Eurythmics.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] According to journalist and author Simon Garfield, "petty jealousies over who sang lead vocals and designed outfits and routines" frequently occurred, and Baker would often clash with both Gee and Martin.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] He refers to the group as "not, after all, a band formed on trust and personal admiration half as much as it was a band formed by the goals of money and success" and therefore prone to infighting and jealousies.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In all, Bucks Fizz had 20 singles reach the UK top 60 between 1981 and 1988.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] On 11 December 1984, Baker was involved in a serious crash in Newcastle upon Tyne, while on tour with the group, when the tour bus crashed into a lorry.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Although she sustained three broken vertebrae in her spine, she made a speedy recovery.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Colleague Mike Nolan, however, suffered serious head injuries, prompting Baker to help establish the HeadFirst charity which supports crash victims, specifically those with head injuries.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] The group's popularity had been diminishing before the crash.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] The group then went through a series of personnel changes after an initial breakup in 1985, with ownership of the name Bucks Fizz being contested.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker left the group in 1993 to focus on developing her career in television.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Around Christmas 2004, some of the band members, including Baker, reunited for live performances.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] While still with Bucks Fizz, Baker started a career as a television presenter in the mid-1980s.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker and Carrie Grant were the two successful candidates from nearly 400 applicants to host the children's show *How Dare You!* in 1984, and each hosted alternate episodes of the series.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In 1985, Baker was one of several celebrities that each hosted Children's ITV for a month.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In 1985 and 1986, she co-hosted *The Saturday Picture Show* with Mark Curry In 1987, she joined *Record Breakers* as a co-host with Roy Castle, and continued as a presenter with new hosts after Castle's death in 1994.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker eventually left the show in 1997, after 10 years.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] She also presented *The Saturday Six O'Clock Show* with Michael Aspel, and had guest appearances on the game shows *Blankety Blank* and *Surprise, Surprise*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In 1988, Baker presented her own TV show *Eggs 'n' Baker*, featuring cooking and guest musical performers, which ran for five years.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In 1989, a seven-part series, *My Secret Desire*, in which a panel attempted to identify the secret ambitions of guests, was hosted by Baker.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] She presented series of six short programmes about food safety, *The Survival Guide to Food*, in 1992.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] After leaving Bucks Fizz, Baker took on other television work alongside *Record Breakers*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In 1987, *The Stage* described her as "ubiquitous ... all over the small screen at the moment".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] She also participated in reality television shows including *I'm Famous and Frightened!* (2004).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] She broke her ankle during a landing on *Drop the Celebrity* (2003).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker released the solo singles: "If Paradise Is Half as Nice" (1987) and "Sensuality" (1992), although neither of these found chart success.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In June 2011, she reached the final of the ITV series *Popstar to Operastar*, where she was beaten into second place by Joe McElderry.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker appeared on *Celebrity Mastermind* in 2013 and 2022.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In the latter appearance, she chose classic Disney Films as her specialist subject.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker was confirmed as the second celebrity to take part in the tenth series of *Dancing on Ice* in October 2017.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] She was the fourth contestant to be eliminated.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker appeared in a special episode of the BBC One soap opera *EastEnders* to celebrate the Eurovision Song Contest 2023; the episode was broadcast on 11 May 2023, the night before the Eurovision semi-final.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] She made her acting debut in the title role in a television production of *Cinderella* on ITV at Christmas 1986.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] At the time, she stated that her other professional commitments would be fitted around her Bucks Fizz timetable.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Her stage acting debut was in *Babes in the Wood*, the 1987 pantomime at the London Palladium, alongside Cannon and Ball, Marti Webb and John Inman.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker played Maid Marian, and Peter Hepple of *The Stage* called her "a new and highly promising recruit to the pantomime ranks".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Among later pantomime appearances at various venues, she took the title roles of *Aladdin* in 1989, *Dick Whittington* in 1993, and *Cinderella* in 1990, 1991 and 1995.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] *The Stage* critic Pat Rusch praised Baker's 1991 turn as Cinderella, writing that she "looked good, played the part with gusto" and sang well, but lamented that the lack of musical numbers in the show meant that she was not able to stand out as much as she could have done otherwise.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker's *Cheryl Baker's Low Calorie Cook Book* (1996) reached number four in the UK book charts.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker, Nolan and Preston reunited as a group under the name the Original Bucks Fizz in 2004.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Preston left the band in 2009 and was replaced by original member Aston.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Following their loss in legal disputes with Gee over the rights to the name in 2011, they renamed the group.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In 2012, they were known as OBF, and later as Cheryl, Mike and Jay – Formerly of Bucks Fizz.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] They later changed their name to the Fizz, and released the albums *The F–Z of Pop* (2017) and *Smoke & Mirrors* (2020) which both charted in the top 30.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In 2006, Baker took her first musical theatre role, as Vi Moore in *Footloose*, based on the 1984 motion picture of the same name, on tour and at the Novello Theatre.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] The same year, she fronted a series of television commercials for Safestyle windows; the company felt that she represented an "instantly recognised image of the 'girl next door'".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] During 2009, Baker toured with the musical *Menopause*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] Baker married Steve Stroud, the bass player in Cliff Richard's band, on 25 January 1992.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] They have twin daughters, born in June 1994 after In vitro fertilisation treatment.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] She is the vice-president of the stillbirth charity Abigail's Footsteps, became an Ambassador of Festival4Stars talent competition after she judged a national final in 2008.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] On *Record Breakers* Baker set a world record for the longest rope slide, descending from Blackpool Tower, and was part of the world's largest Jazz ensemble and the longest *Riverdance* line.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/cheryl-baker] In 1987, Baker and Gyles Brandreth kissed onscreen for three minutes and 33 seconds, longer than the then-record longest onscreen kiss.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] A **Children's hospice** is a hospice specifically designed to help children and young people who are not expected to reach adulthood with the emotional and physical challenges they face, and also to provide respite care for their families.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Children's hospice services work with families from all faiths, cultures and ethnic backgrounds and respect the importance of religious customs and cultural needs that are essential to the daily lives of each family.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Many have a chaplain who is familiar with a variety of faiths and customs.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Each service is typically an independent charity which relies on public support to continue their work.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Children's hospice services are dedicated to improving the quality of life of children and young people who are not expected to live to reach adulthood and their families.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] They provide flexible, practical and free support at home and in the hospice to the entire family, often over many years and at any stage of the child's or young person's illness.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] This includes short breaks and daytime activities enabling families to get a rest; help with the control of pain or other distressing symptoms; and support for family members, including brothers and sisters.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] When the end of a child's life approaches, children's hospice services are there to provide end-of-life care and bereavement support for as long as it's needed, helping families and friends approach death with dignity and peace.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Helen House in Oxfordshire was the world's first children's hospice.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Helen House sprang from a friendship between Sister Frances Dominica and the parents of a seriously ill little girl called Helen, who lived at home with her family but required 24-hour care.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] The first children's hospice in Scotland Rachel House, run by Children's Hospice Association Scotland opened in March 1996.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] There are now over 40 operational children's hospice services open across the UK.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Children's hospice services in England receive an average of 5% government funding and rely heavily on public donations.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] The children's hospice movement is still in a relatively early stage in the United States, where many of the functions of a children's hospice are provided by children's hospitals.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] In 1983, of the 1,400 hospices in the United States, only four were able to accept children.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] When physicians have to decide that a child can no longer be medically cured, along with the parents a decision is made to end care, keeping in mind the best interest of the child.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] When a decision between the parents and physicians cannot be reached, which is a very small percentage.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] The physicians are then not obligated to provide any therapy care that the doctors have not deemed necessary towards the care goals of the child.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Most parents of the children that have serious development disorders actively share the end of life decision-making process.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] The main factors that parents take into consideration when making end-of-life care decisions are the importance to advocate for the best interest of their child.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Also, the visible suffering, the remaining quality of life, and the child's will to survive is an influence.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Through the efforts of CHI, most of the over 3,000 hospices in the U.S. will now consider accepting children.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Also, approximately 450 programs have children-specific hospice, palliative, or home care services.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Children's hospitals today have ethics consultation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Ethics consultation is a conference that is intended to help Patients, Staff and other resolve ethical concerns.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] It all begins with taking into consideration of the patient's ethical beliefs, families, and those professionals involved in the case.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Different individuals tend to abide by different ethical beliefs and ethical dilemmas tend to rise out of the difference in values or the priority of those shared values.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Additional Institutions that care for those patients have certain set of values.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Some institutions are specialized in prioritizing patient care and others are devoted to research.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Some Hospitals are public, others are private.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Some serve their community and values can vary from community to community which can also cause disagreements.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Institutions and hospitals also have value of their own that are written in their Mission Statement of the Institution.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Ethic committees began in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] The original purpose was to bring voices to conversations about ethically controversial clinical situations.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] The original voices brought to the table of discussion of ethic committees were Theologians, philosophers, social scientists, scholars in the humanities and other experts.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Over the years ethics consultations have become more widely accepted.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Most hospitals in the United States and across the world now have ethics committees and process for ethics consultation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] In the early 1970s many experts realized that the medical education was not designed and physicians were not trained to deal with ethical issues associated with new technologies such as mechanical ventilation, dialysis and transplantation.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] Before the creation of such technology kidney failure was sure to be fatal, now physicians were starting to make choices about where, when, and how someone could die.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/children-s-hospice] One of the solutions was to invite theologians, philosophers and social scientist that would help physicians think and solve complicated ethical issues.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe branched out to stage acting in 2007, starring in the West End and Broadway productions of *Equus*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He returned to Broadway in the musical *How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying* (2011), earning a Grammy Award nomination.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] His other Broadway roles include Martin McDonagh's drama *The Cripple of Inishmaan* (2014) and Stephen Sondheim's musical *Merrily We Roll Along* (2023), the latter of which earned him a Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Musical and another Grammy Award nomination.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He also starred in the London revivals of Tom Stoppard's *Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead* (2017) and Samuel Beckett's *Endgame* (2020).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe also expanded his film roles, acting in a variety of genres such as the horror film *The Woman in Black* (2012), surreal drama *Swiss Army Man* (2016), thriller *Now You See Me 2* (2016), and comedy *The Lost City* (2022).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He also portrayed Allen Ginsberg in the biopic *Kill Your Darlings* (2013) and "Weird Al" Yankovic in the musical parody *Weird: The Al Yankovic Story* (2022).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The latter earned him nominations for a Primetime Emmy Award and a British Academy Television Award.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He also played multiple roles in the anthology comedy series *Miracle Workers* from 2019 to 2023.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe has contributed to various charities, including Demelza Hospice Care for Children and the Trevor Project.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The latter awarded him its Hero Award in 2011 for his advocacy with LGBTQ youth.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Daniel Jacob Radcliffe was born on 23 July 1989 at Queen Charlotte's and Chelsea Hospital in the Hammersmith district of London, the only child of casting agent Marcia Jeannine Gresham (née Jacobson) and literary agent Alan George Radcliffe.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] His Jewish mother, born in South Africa, traces her ancestry to Ashkenazi Jewish immigrants from Germany, Lithuania, Poland, and Russia, and was raised in the English town of Westcliff-on-Sea in Essex.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] His Northern Irish father was raised in a "very working-class" Protestant family in Banbridge in County Down.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2019, he explored both sides of his family history in the BBC genealogy series *Who Do You Think You Are?*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe's parents had both acted as children.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] As a casting agent, his mother was involved in BBC productions including *The Inspector Lynley Mysteries*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe was educated at three private schools for boys in London: Redcliffe School, Sussex House School, and the City of London School.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] After the release of the first *Harry Potter* film, attending school proved difficult for him as some fellow pupils became hostile, though he states they were just trying to "have a crack at the kid that plays Harry Potter" rather than acting out of jealousy.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] As his acting career began to consume his schedule, he continued his education through on-set tutors.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He has admitted to not being a very good student, considering school useless and finding the work "really difficult".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He achieved A grades in the three AS level exams that he took in 2006, but decided to take a break from education and did not attend university.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Part of his reasoning was he already knew he wanted to be an actor and screenwriter, and it would be difficult to have a normal university experience.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe first expressed a desire to act at age five.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] After one of his mother's casting agent friends secured him an audition, he made his acting debut at age ten in BBC One's two-part adaptation of the Charles Dickens novel *David Copperfield* (1999), portraying the title character as a young boy.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He made his film debut in *The Tailor of Panama* (2001), an American film based on John le Carré's 1996 spy novel, which was a moderate commercial success.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2000, producer David Heyman met Radcliffe while he was at the theatre with his father, a well-known literary agent whom Heyman was friends with.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He asked him to audition for the role of Harry Potter for the film adaptation of *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone*, the best-selling book by British author J.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Rowling had been searching for an unknown British actor to personify the character, and the film's director Chris Columbus recalled thinking, "This is what I want.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] This is Harry Potter" after he saw a video of the young actor in *David Copperfield*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Eight months later, following several auditions, Radcliffe was selected to play the part.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Rowling endorsed the selection, saying: "I don't think Chris Columbus could have found a better Harry." Radcliffe's parents originally turned down the offer, as they had been told that it would involve six films shot in Los Angeles.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Warner Bros. instead offered Radcliffe a two-film contract with shooting in the UK; Radcliffe was unsure at the time if he would act in more than two *Harry Potter* films.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The release of *Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone* took place in 2001.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe received a seven-figure salary for the lead role, but asserted that the fee was "not that important" to him; his parents chose to invest the money for him.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The film was highly popular and was met with positive reviews, and critics took notice of Radcliffe: "Radcliffe is the embodiment of every reader's imagination.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] It is wonderful to see a young hero who is so scholarly looking and filled with curiosity and who connects with very real emotions, from solemn intelligence and the delight of discovery to deep family longing," wrote Bob Graham of the *San Francisco Chronicle*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] A year later, Radcliffe starred in *Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets*, the second installment of the series.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Reviewers were positive about the lead actors' performances but had polarising opinions on the film overall.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] *Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban* (2004) was the third film in the series.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe's performance was criticised by *The New York Times* film critic A.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Scott, who felt that co-star Emma Watson had to carry him with her performance.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] *Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire* (2005) was the second-highest grossing *Harry Potter* film at that point, and Radcliffe singled out the humour as a reason for the film's creative success.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The future of the *Harry Potter* franchise was put into question when Radcliffe, Watson, and co-star Rupert Grint hesitated to sign on to continue their roles.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe reprised the role of Harry for the fifth time in *Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix* (2007).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe stated that director David Yates and co-star Imelda Staunton made *Order of the Phoenix* the "most fun" film to work on in the series.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] His performance earned him several award nominations, and he received the 2008 National Movie Award for "Best Male Performance".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe, Grint, and Watson left imprints of their hands, feet, and wands in front of Grauman's Chinese Theatre in Hollywood.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] *Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince*, the series' sixth instalment, was released in July 2009.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe received nominations for Best Male Performance and Global Superstar at the 2010 MTV Movie Awards.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] For financial and scripting reasons, the last *Harry Potter* book (*Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows*) was divided into two films that were shot back-to-back.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] This decision drew criticism from the series' fans, but Radcliffe defended the split, stating that it would have been impossible to properly adapt the final novel into a single film.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The two-film finale, *Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows – Part 1* and *Part 2*, was released in November 2010 and July 2011, respectively.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] While *Deathly Hallows – Part 1* grossed $960 million, *Deathly Hallows – Part 2* grossed more than $1.3 billion worldwide; as of May 2019, it was the 11th-highest-grossing film of all time.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] *Deathly Hallows – Part 2* was critically acclaimed, as was Radcliffe's performance; Ann Hornaday of *The Washington Post* asked, "Who could have predicted that Radcliffe, Grint and Watson would turn out to be good actors"?
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Critic Rex Reed remarked, "Frankly, I'm sorry to see [Radcliffe] go"; Roger Ebert gave the film a highly positive review, but felt that Radcliffe, Grint and Watson were "upstaged by the supporting [actors]".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe acknowledged that some people would never be able to separate him from the Harry Potter character; however, he has said he is "proud to be associated with this film series forever".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Despite positive feelings about the films, he has no interest in doing more *Harry Potter* films.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] After Rowling hinted about writing an eighth book, Radcliffe was asked if he would do another *Harry Potter* film, to which he replied, "[It is] very doubtful.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] I think 10 years is a long time to spend with one character".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2002, Radcliffe made his stage debut as a celebrity guest in a West End production of *The Play What I Wrote*, directed by Kenneth Branagh—who also appeared with him in the second *Harry Potter* film.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He appeared in the film *December Boys*, an Australian family drama about four orphans that was shot in 2005 and released to theaters in mid-September 2007.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] On 13 April 2006, a portrait of Radcliffe by Stuart Pearson Wright was unveiled as part of a new exhibition opening at the National Theatre, before being moved to the National Portrait Gallery.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2007, Radcliffe co-starred with Carey Mulligan in *My Boy Jack*, a television drama film shown on ITV.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The film received mostly positive reviews, with several critics praising Radcliffe's performance as an eighteen-year-old who goes missing in action during a battle.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe stated, "For many people my age, the First World War is just a topic in a history book.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] At age seventeen, in a bid to demonstrate that he was prepared for adult roles, Radcliffe starred in a West End revival of Peter Shaffer's play *Equus* at the Gielgud Theatre.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The piece had not been revived since its first run in 1973.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe took on the lead role of Alan Strang, a stable boy who has an obsession with horses.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The role generated significant pre-opening media interest, as Radcliffe performed a nude scene.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] *Equus* opened on 27 February 2007 and ran until 9 June 2007.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe's performance was acclaimed, as critics were impressed by the nuance and depth of his against-type role.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe continued in the lead role, starring alongside Kate Mulgrew, Anna Camp, and his *Harry Potter* co-star Richard Griffiths.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe was nervous about reprising the role on Broadway as he considered American audiences to be more discerning than those in London.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe's performance was nominated for a Drama Desk Award.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] After voicing a character in *The Simpsons* episode "Treehouse of Horror XXI" in late 2010, Radcliffe debuted as J.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Pierrepont Finch in a 2011 Broadway revival of *How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying* at the Al Hirschfeld Theatre.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The role had previously been played by Robert Morse and Matthew Broderick.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Other cast members included John Larroquette, Rose Hemingway and Mary Faber.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The production itself later received nine Tony Award nominations.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe left the show on 1 January 2012.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe's first post-*Harry Potter* project was the 2012 horror film *The Woman in Black*, adapted from the 1983 novel by Susan Hill.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The film was released on 3 February 2012 in the United States and Canada, and was released on 10 February in the UK.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe portrays a man sent to deal with the legal matters of a mysterious woman who has just died, and soon after he begins to experience strange events and hauntings from the ghost of a woman dressed in black.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He has said he was "incredibly excited" to be part of the film and described the script as "beautifully written".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2013, he portrayed American beat poet Allen Ginsberg in the thriller drama *Kill Your Darlings*, directed by John Krokidas.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He also starred in an Irish-Canadian romantic comedy film *The F Word* (2013) directed by Michael Dowseand written by Elan Mastai, based on TJ Dawe and Michael Rinaldi's play *Toothpaste and Cigars* and then he starred in *Horns*, an American dark fantasy horror film directed by Alexandre Aja.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Both of the films premiered at the 38th Toronto International Film Festival.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Also in 2013, Radcliffe performed at the Noël Coward Theatre in the stage play revival of Martin McDonagh's dark comedy *The Cripple of Inishmaan* as the lead, Billy Claven, for which he won the WhatsOnStage Award for Best Actor in a Play.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe starred as Igor in a science fiction horror film *Victor Frankenstein* (2015), directed by Paul McGuigan and written by Max Landis.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The film was based on contemporary adaptations of Mary Shelley's 1818 novel *Frankenstein.* He also starred as Sam Houser, one of the founders of Rockstar Games, in the biographical drama film *The Gamechangers*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2016, Radcliffe portrayed Manny, a talkative corpse, in the indie film *Swiss Army Man* with Paul Dano.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] That same year, he starred in the critically acclaimed independent film *Imperium* (2016) alongside Toni Collette and Tracy Letts.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He played Nate Foster, an idealistic FBI agent who goes undercover to take down a radical white supremacy group.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe starred off-Broadway at The Public Theater in a documentary theatre piece titled *Privacy*, playing the role of The Writer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2017, he starred as Yossi Ghinsberg in the thriller *Jungle*, which was based on an internationally best-selling memoir of the same name by Yossi Ghinsberg.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2018, Radcliffe portrayed a pilot smuggling drugs across borders in the independent action-thriller *Beast of Burden* directed by Jesper Ganslandt.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The same year, he returned to Broadway in the ninety-minute comedy play *The Lifespan of a Fact* at Studio 54 Theatre with Bobby Cannavale and Cherry Jones.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The play revolves around a determined young fact checker who goes up against his demanding editor and an unorthodox author.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] As part of his research for the role, Radcliffe spent a day working in the fact checking department of *The New Yorker*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2019, Radcliffe starred as Craig in the TBS comedy limited series *Miracle Workers* based on the book by Simon Rich.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The show's second season premiered on 28 January 2020.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He voice–starred as Rex Dasher, a secret agent who helps Marla, in the animated film *Playmobil: The Movie* directed by Lino DiSalvo.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2020, Radcliffe starred as Miles in the action comedy film *Guns Akimbo* directed by Jason Lei Howden and co-starring Samara Weaving and Natasha Liu Bordizzo.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He also starred as Tim Jenkin in the thriller film *Escape from Pretoria*, based on the real-life prison escape by three young political prisoners from jail in South Africa in 1979.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He also played the role of Prince Frederick in the Netflix special *Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt* opposite Ellie Kemper.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe reunited with multiple cast members of the *Harry Potter* film series for an HBO Max special titled *Harry Potter 20th Anniversary: Return to Hogwarts*, which was released on 1 January 2022.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe stars as the villain, Abigail Fairfax, in the action-adventure comedy film *The Lost City*, opposite Sandra Bullock and Channing Tatum.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He portrayed musician "Weird Al" Yankovic in *Weird: The Al Yankovic Story*, a biographical parody film produced for The Roku Channel, for which he received his first Primetime Emmy Award nomination.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In early 2022, Radcliffe returned to the stage acting alongside Jonathan Groff and Lindsay Mendez in the New York Theatre Workshop revival of the Stephen Sondheim musical *Merrily We Roll Along*, in which he played Charley Kringas.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The revival started on 21 November 2022 and opened on 12 December 2022, running for a limited engagement through 8 January 2023, before transferring to a critically acclaimed run on Broadway.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] For his performance, Radcliffe won the Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Musical.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] A film version of *Merrily We Roll Along*, starring Radcliffe and his co-stars from their stage production, had been picked up by Sony Pictures Classics.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The release date for the U.S. was set for 5 December 2025.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe returned to Broadway in the interactive one-man play *Every Brilliant Thing* at the Hudson Theatre in February 2026, earning a second Tony nomination.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In March 2026, it was announced that *Law & Order: Special Victims Unit* star Mariska Hargitay would replace Radcliffe in the play starting May 2026.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe is set to star in the war thriller *Trust the Man*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In May 2025, it was announced that Radcliffe would star in the Tina Fey-produced television series *The Fall and Rise of Reggie Dinkins* alongside Tracy Morgan and Erika Alexander.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] The first episode premiered in January 2026.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In May 2026, *The Fall and Rise of Reggie Dinkins* was renewed for a second season.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He has also established himself as a stage actor, making his Broadway debut in a revival of the Peter Shaffer play *Equus* (2007).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe has lent his support to various charitable organisations.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He designed the Cu-Bed for Habitat's VIP Kids range (a cube made of eight smaller ones which can be made into a bed, chaise-longue or chair) with all the royalties from the sale of the bed going directly to his favourite charity, Demelza House Children's Hospice in Sittingbourne, Kent.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe has urged fans to make donations to the charity's Candle for Care programme in lieu of giving him Christmas presents.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2008, he was among several celebrities who donated their old glasses to an exhibit honouring victims of the Holocaust.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] During the Broadway run of *Equus* he auctioned off a pair of jeans and other items worn in the show, for New-York-based Broadway Cares/Equity Fights AIDS and was a presenter at the 2011 Gypsy of the Year competition.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He has also made donations in support of Get Connected UK, a London-based free confidential national helpline for troubled youth.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe is a supporter of the Labour Party.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He previously supported the Liberal Democrats, and endorsed then-Lib Dem leader Nick Clegg in the 2010 general election.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2012, however, he switched his political alignment to Labour, citing disillusionment with the performance of Clegg and the Liberal Democrats while in government, and approving of then-Labour leader Ed Miliband.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2015, he endorsed Jeremy Corbyn's Labour Party leadership campaign.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He told *The Big Issue*, "I feel like this show of sincerity by a man who has been around long enough and stuck to his beliefs long enough that he knows them and doesn't have to be scripted is what is making people sit up and get excited.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2009, Radcliffe stated that although he considers himself a "fierce patriot" he supports abolishing the British monarchy and replacing it with a republic, adding that the monarchy "symbolized a lot of what is wrong with the country".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He supports British unionism, and opposed the 2014 Scottish independence referendum because he "personally like[s] the UK being how it is".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe is supportive of the LGBTQ community.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Speaking out against homophobia, he began filming public service announcements in 2009 for The Trevor Project, promoting awareness of gay teen suicide prevention.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He first learned of the organization while performing *Equus* on Broadway in 2008 and has contributed financially to it.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He said in a 2010 interview, "I have always hated anybody who is not tolerant of gay men or lesbians or bisexuals.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Now I am in the very fortunate position where I can actually help or do something about it." In the same interview, he stressed the importance of public figures advocating for equal rights.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He received The Trevor Project's Hero Award in 2011 for his contributions.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In June 2020, amid controversy over *Harry Potter* author J.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Rowling's remarks on transgender people, Radcliffe penned an essay published by The Trevor Project in which he voiced support for the transgender community and expressed regret that Rowling's statements tarnished some fans' experience of the *Harry Potter* books.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe splits his time between homes in the Fulham area of London and the West Village neighbourhood of New York City's Manhattan borough.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He has been in a relationship with American actress Erin Darke since 2012, after having met on the set of *Kill Your Darlings*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] They have a son, who was born in April 2023.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe is close with his family, whom he credits for keeping him grounded.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2024, he had said that his parents, who had been married for 30 years, had inspired him in his relationship with Darke.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In August 2010, he became teetotal after finding himself becoming too reliant on alcohol, particularly during the filming of *Half-Blood Prince*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In March 2020, he appeared as the guest on BBC Radio 4's *Desert Island Discs*, during which he discussed his alcohol misuse during his teens, his decision to become teetotal, and how his parents' support and staying in his native England helped him cope with fame.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe was reported to have earned £1 million for the first *Harry Potter* film, around £15 million for the sixth, and around £39 million for the final two movies combined.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In all, he is estimated to have made a total of £75.4 million from the entire franchise.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] He appeared on the *Sunday Times* Rich List in 2006, which estimated his personal fortune to be £14 million, making him one of the richest young people in the UK.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In March 2009, he was ranked at number one on the *Forbes* "Most Valuable Young Stars" list, and by April *The Daily Telegraph* measured his net worth at £30 million, making him the 12th richest young person in the UK.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe was considered to be the richest teenager in England later that year.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In February 2010, he was named the sixth highest-paid Hollywood male star and placed at number five on *Forbes*' December list of Hollywood's highest-grossing actors with a film revenue of US$780 million, mainly due to *Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows* being released that year.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] As of 2021, Radcliffe's net worth is estimated at £95 million.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In 2008, Radcliffe revealed that he has a mild form of the neurological disorder dyspraxia, which sometimes prevents him from doing simple activities such as writing or tying his shoelaces.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] In early 2026 he discussed having given up smoking after having smoked "pretty heavily" for 20 years.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Radcliffe stated of his beliefs in 2012: "There was never [religious] faith in the house.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] I think of myself as being Jewish and Irish, despite the fact that I'm English." He has said that his family are "Christmas tree Jews" and he said "I'm an atheist, but I'm very proud of being Jewish.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] It means I have a good work ethic, and you get Jewish humour and you're allowed to tell Jewish jokes." In 2009, he stated that he was an atheist and said, "I'm very relaxed about [being an atheist].
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] I don't preach my atheism, but I have a huge amount of respect for people like Richard Dawkins who do.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] Anything he does on television, I will watch." He said in 2012, "I'm an atheist, and a militant atheist when religion starts impacting on legislation." In 2019, he described himself as "agnostic leaning toward atheism".
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/daniel-radcliffe] This refers to the amount of money taken by films in which they have appeared, not their personal income.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry began work in 'The Observatory', a South London vintage clothes shop.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He joined a modelling agency where he participated in campaigns for Ted Baker, French Connection, Toni & Guy and Burton.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] In 2009 he co-founded 'October House', a tailoring brand making bespoke suits from British fabrics.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Clients include David Gandy, Scott Parker, Miles Kane, Mark Cavendish, Jamie Scallion and Johnny Harris.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry reportedly wore a three piece suit while presenting the Capital Breakfast Show.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] In 2001, Dave Berry started presenting Nickelodeon's music chart show "N-List" alongside Kelle Bryan.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] From 2008 until 2014, Berry presented episodes of *The Hot Desk* on ITV2.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He co-presented the 2012 series *Beat TV* on ITV2 alongside Laura Whitmore and Darren McMullen.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Since 2013, Berry has been a regular panellist on Keith Lemon's *Through the Keyhole* on ITV.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He has also been a regular reporter on Holly Willoughby's *Surprise Surprise*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry presented *Soccer Aid: Extra Time* in 2010 and again in 2012.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He presented the show *Takeaway My Takeaway* on Channel 4.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He has been nominated for a Rose D'Or Award, Broadcast Award and a BAFTA award.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry's radio career began on *Capital Radio* in 2007 where he presented the Saturday afternoon show.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Soon after, he was employed by alternative indie rock station XFM whose previous presenters include Ricky Gervais, Stephen Merchant, Simon Pegg, Jimmy Carr and Russell Brand.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He hosted the *Dave Berry Saturday Show* for 12 weeks, the drivetime show for almost two years, and the *XFM Breakfast Show* which achieved some of XFM's highest RAJAR figures.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] On 15 April 2011 he left XFM to present the weekend breakfast show on Capital Radio (now known as *Capital London*).
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] On 25 December 2011, he presented his final weekend Capital London, after the announcement that he would replace Johnny Vaughan on *Capital Breakfast (London)* on 3 January 2012.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He hosted the Capital Breakfast (London) show every weekday morning from 6am - 10am with a national broadcast across the Capital network on Saturdays.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry has won the Radio Academy Gold Award for Breakfast Show of the Year and is a two-time winner of the TRIC Award for Best Radio/ Digital Radio Programme.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] In April 2017, Berry left Capital and subsequently has been replaced on the Capital Breakfast (London) show by Roman Kemp.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He began presenting 4-7pm on Absolute Radio from 2 October 2017 with his co-host Matt Dyson.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry also presented a 7-10pm show on Absolute Radio's sister station Absolute Radio 90s every Monday-Thursday.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] In March 2018, it was confirmed that Berry would replace Christian O'Connell as the host of the Absolute Radio Breakfast Show.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry began presenting the Absolute Radio Breakfast Show on 4 June 2018 where he was joined by Dyson and the show's newsreaders Glenn Moore and Emma Jones.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] As of October 2019, *The Dave Berry Breakfast Show* had 2.2 million listeners, a record for the station.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry continues to host the flagship Dave Berry Breakfast Show every weekday morning from 6am across the Absolute Radio network, with the broadcast now streaming via Bauer Media's updated Rayo audio platform.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] The show's on-air lineup has seen significant updates; long-term travel presenter Emma Jones departed the program in late 2025, and award-winning broadcaster Rich Williams subsequently joined the morning team alongside Berry, Matt Dyson, and Andrea Fox.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry's show on Absolute Radio is also released daily as a podcast under the title *The Dave Berry Breakfast Show*.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] In 2019, Berry launched the podcast *Dave Berry's DadPod* for Bauer Media Group, discussing the topic of parenthood with guests including John Thomson, Rob Beckett and Emma Willis.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] The first series of 6 episodes premiered in October 2019, and was selected as a UK Pick of the Month by Spotify.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry has also appeared regularly on the Empire podcast.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry regularly contributes to The Guardian, and contributed to *HuffPost* in July 2012 and again in 2016-2017.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He has also contributed to The Daily Telegraph, Q, and Empire.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Berry married charity Communications and Marketing Consultant Sarah-Jane Davies in March 2018.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He was engaged to Sugababes singer Heidi Range, but the engagement was called off.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] In 2012 he was appointed ambassador for the Charlton Athletic Community Trust.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He is ambassador for YouCan Youth Cancer Support which operates in London, Kent and the south east, and Balls To Cancer - a Midland's based charity raising awareness for male cancer.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] He stated in *The Guardian* that a disastrous, bleeding tattoo at 17 was a 'moment that changed me'.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] On 28 August 2018, Berry announced on his Absolute Radio breakfast show that he and Davies were expecting their first child.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/dave-berry-presenter] Their daughter Evangeline was born in December 2018.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/demelza-hospice-care-for-children] With two residential hospices in Sittingbourne, Kent and Eltham, South East London, and a community hub in East Sussex, Demelza provides clinical care, symptom and medication management, step-down care and end of life care.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/demelza-hospice-care-for-children] Support services include: day care, short breaks, community care, support during pregnancy, family liaison support, sibling support, creative therapies, bereavement services, practical support, transition and memory making.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/demelza-hospice-care-for-children] Demelza is supported by a number of Vice Presidents - celebrity ambassadors who help raise awareness of and funds for Demelza.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/demelza-hospice-care-for-children] These include: actors Daniel Radcliffe and Sally Lindsay, Olympic Gold Medallists Robin Cousins and Jayne Torvill, former England footballer and BBC presenter Gary Lineker, Absolute Radio host Dave Berry), TV presenter and singer Cheryl Baker and broadcast journalist Sir Martyn Lewis.
[src:demelza-hospice-care-for-children/demelza-hospice-care-for-children] The holder of the post of Archbishop of Canterbury is also a Vice President.
